The Murang&rsquo;a government is using the Murang&rsquo;a County Women&rsquo;s Sacco and community health workers in a door-to-door campaign to register voters as the Tuesday deadline approaches. The aim is to list more than 30,000 new voters every day in the remaining week of the exercise.Governor Mwangi Wairia said only 63,000 people have registered as voters so far, against a target of 227,000.He was addressing the two groups in Murang&rsquo;a town yesterday, accompanied by Transport PS Irungu Nyakera and his Housing counterpart Idah Munano. Wairia said the target is to register 160,000 voters.&ldquo;We only have five days remaining to ensure all unregistered adults are listed and drastic measures have to be taken,&rdquo; he said.The governor said the women&rsquo;s sacco, with more than 35,000 members, has networks across the county and will easily mobilise people to register.Wairia said the women will conduct a door-to-door campaign. &ldquo;Those who are not registered will be taken to the nearest registration centres,&rdquo; he said.Wairia said the women can net 25,000 people every day if each registers one person. &ldquo;For the remaining days, we will focus all our efforts towards ensuring everybody is registered for them to exercise their democratic right of voting,&rdquo; he said.Wairia said the county government has about 1,000 community health workers, who will be dispatched to the grassroots to augment the effort.He said the community health workers live in the villages and can identify disadvantaged people unable to walk to the registration centres.